  "prompt": "In genetics, what is an example of a monohybrid cross offspring?",
  "response": "A classic example of a monohybrid cross offspring is found in Mendel's pea plants. When Mendel crossed a pea plant that was homozygous for the dominant trait of purple flowers (PP) with a pea plant that was homozygous for the recessive trait of white flowers (pp), the offspring (F1 generation) were all heterozygous (Pp) and displayed the dominant trait of purple flowers.\n\nTo summarize, the offspring of this monohybrid cross were all heterozygous (Pp) and had purple flowers, demonstrating the dominance of the purple flower allele over the white flower allele.",
